1
00:00:40,840 --> 00:00:45,410
So I get this phone call, July 30th, 2005,
from Steven Spielberg.

2
00:00:46,120 --> 00:00:47,910
He calls me up in
his jovial self and he says,

3
00:00:48,280 --> 00:00:50,950
"Michael, I want you to direct
this movie called Transformers."

4
00:00:51,400 --> 00:00:54,210
I'm like, "Okay, Steven,
well, that sounds great.

5
00:00:54,680 --> 00:00:56,820
"Let me think about it,
and I'll get back to you.”

6
00:00:57,200 --> 00:00:58,110
I hung up the phone

7
00:00:58,320 --> 00:01:00,710
and in the 30 seconds everything
that goes through your brain.

8
00:01:01,120 --> 00:01:04,910
"Is that that little robot toy movie?"
"Is that like a Small Soldiers movie?"

9
00:01:05,519 --> 00:01:08,190
"That was just Steven Spielberg
calling me up. Oh, my God!"

10
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:10,600
"This is one of my idols,
wants me to direct a movie

11
00:01:10,960 --> 00:01:12,399
"that he wants to
be involved in."

12
00:01:12,680 --> 00:01:13,620
So I thought about it.

13
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:16,580
I called Adam Goodman, president
of the studio at DreamWorks.

14
00:01:17,040 --> 00:01:18,580
l said, "Adam, so what is
this Transformers movie?"

15
00:01:18,880 --> 00:01:20,420
He goes,
"Why don't you think about it?"

16
00:01:20,720 --> 00:01:22,440
Adam convinced me to
go to Transformer school,

17
00:01:22,760 --> 00:01:24,550
which is in Hasbro
in Rhode Island.

18
00:01:24,880 --> 00:01:26,560
And I'm like, "Okay,
well, let's make the trek.”

19
00:01:26,880 --> 00:01:29,020
So the next morning
we went into Hasbro.

20
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:32,810
You pass this hallway of all
the famous toys we all grew up with.

21
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:34,940
We sat in this
big conference room.

22
00:01:35,240 --> 00:01:37,130
I mean, they must have
had 25 people in there,

23
00:01:37,480 --> 00:01:40,430
all trying to convince
me to do Transformers,

24
00:01:40,920 --> 00:01:42,360
and they started with
Transformer school

25
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:45,200
which is, they basically take you
through the entire lore of Transformers.

26
00:01:45,640 --> 00:01:48,060
Now, I have been offered a lot of
comic book, superhero movies

27
00:01:48,480 --> 00:01:50,650
in my short film career.

28
00:01:51,040 --> 00:01:53,780
And I have always said no because
it really hasn't appealed to me.

29
00:01:54,240 --> 00:01:58,449
But one thing I did spark to recently
was Japanese anime movies.

30
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:03,050
I just love their visuals. It's just a
really unique type of cartoon.

31
00:02:03,560 --> 00:02:06,510
And I'm sitting in this Transformer,
I guess, like, lecture.

32
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:10,229
I kept looking at this artwork
of just a multitude of images

33
00:02:10,759 --> 00:02:13,079
and there was something
from this Japanese artist.

34
00:02:13,480 --> 00:02:17,940
He had some amazingly dark,
cool images that...

35
00:02:18,640 --> 00:02:20,529
That just right there
in the room inspired me.

36
00:02:20,880 --> 00:02:23,440
I kept thinking to myself,
"I need to make this very real.

37
00:02:23,880 --> 00:02:24,960
"I need to make this cool.”

38
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:27,799
I kept thinking about cars
transforming at 80 miles an hour.

39
00:02:28,240 --> 00:02:31,890
Action images would just
kind of come to my mind,

40
00:02:32,480 --> 00:02:34,760
of, like, "Why would I be
interested in doing this movie?"

41
00:02:35,160 --> 00:02:36,670
I did like the lore
of Transformers.

42
00:02:36,960 --> 00:02:39,130
It's very noble, it's got good
morals, it's interesting.

43
00:02:39,520 --> 00:02:41,310
But it's like, how do
you make Transformers

44
00:02:41,640 --> 00:02:42,799
understandable to an adult

45
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:45,209
who has no knowledge
of what Transformer toys are?

46
00:02:45,600 --> 00:02:48,340
We broadened the story in terms
of bringing in the American military.

47
00:02:48,800 --> 00:02:52,770
It's this big story, but it kind of comes
down to this little story on Earth,

48
00:02:53,400 --> 00:02:56,070
which is all about Sam
and having these glasses.

49
00:02:56,520 --> 00:03:00,100
This is kind of how the birth
of Transformers happened.

50
00:03:03,840 --> 00:03:06,400
l have always had the lucky fortune
of working with military equipment

51
00:03:06,840 --> 00:03:09,650
before anybody else, such as
these Ospreys right here.

52
00:03:10,120 --> 00:03:12,190
They have never
been used in a movie,

53
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:18,530
and I don't think many people
have shot that Stealth 117 either.

54
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:21,020
So I've got this hotline
to the Pentagon.

55
00:03:21,320 --> 00:03:25,780
I've got this relationship with
the film liaison, Phil Strub,

56
00:03:26,480 --> 00:03:30,829
who helped me on Armageddon
where we worked with the Air Force.

57
00:03:31,520 --> 00:03:34,500
And Pearl Harbor, where we worked
with the Navy and all the branches.

58
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,790
And I called Phil up and I said, "Phil,
I'm gonna be doing this movie.

59
00:03:39,400 --> 00:03:41,820
"It's a fantasy movie called
Transformers."

60
00:03:42,240 --> 00:03:43,920
And he goes,
"Oh, the kids’ toy, huh?"

61
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:47,750
He said, "Well, Mike, you know,
if we did have alien robots on Earth,

62
00:03:48,320 --> 00:03:50,070
"[ think the American military
would be involved.

63
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:52,120
"And we will bring the fight
anywhere we have to.

64
00:03:52,440 --> 00:03:54,829
"So let me read the script.
I'm excited to read it."

65
00:03:55,240 --> 00:04:00,750
And I guess the rest is history.
He loved it.

66
00:04:01,600 --> 00:04:03,700
And then it's a matter of me
going to different bases

67
00:04:04,080 --> 00:04:08,790
and trying to convince bases
to be...Imitate Qatar,

68
00:04:09,520 --> 00:04:13,030
which is the forward command
for the whole Middle East.

69
00:04:13,600 --> 00:04:16,969
And we found Holloman
Air Force Base in New Mexico,

70
00:04:17,519 --> 00:04:19,240
which kind of has these
white sands

71
00:04:19,560 --> 00:04:23,180
which are test missile ranges
for, I think, the Army.

72
00:04:25,760 --> 00:04:28,670
Right here, this was done at
Edwards. These are two F-22s,

73
00:04:29,160 --> 00:04:32,670
which are the brand-new planes
that are costing $130 million each.

74
00:04:33,240 --> 00:04:36,650
They can take out six F-16s before
they can even be spotted.

75
00:04:37,200 --> 00:04:38,740
They are just deadly lethal,

76
00:04:39,040 --> 00:04:41,250
and of course, I was the
first to use those as well.

77
00:04:43,240 --> 00:04:44,710
Why does the military
let me use this stuff?

78
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,810
Because they look good at
what they do in my movies.

79
00:04:48,280 --> 00:04:52,809
And working with these
men and women...

80
00:04:53,760 --> 00:04:56,390
You know, I have done many years
of working with them, in movies,

81
00:04:56,840 --> 00:05:00,030
and, you know, they are
really great people.

82
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:01,680
And they're really dedicated.

83
00:05:01,920 --> 00:05:07,360
And I really admire them for
the service they do for the country.

84
00:05:08,200 --> 00:05:11,010
And, you know, they don't
work for a great wage,

85
00:05:11,480 --> 00:05:14,890
but they're just so dedicated
to the country and...

86
00:05:16,520 --> 00:05:20,140
You know, so, like, just diligent
and just, you know...

87
00:05:20,720 --> 00:05:23,530
I find many of them so intelligent,

88
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:28,850
and it's always been a great experience
when I've worked on these bases.

89
00:05:29,600 --> 00:05:32,300
And I really have fond memories
of it.

90
00:05:32,760 --> 00:05:35,289
And very much, they're impressed
with our film industry

91
00:05:35,720 --> 00:05:37,820
because we work very much
like the military works,

92
00:05:38,200 --> 00:05:41,710
in terms of the different hierarchy
and how it works on our sets and crews.

93
00:05:42,280 --> 00:05:44,450
And they are always very sceptical
when we show up,

94
00:05:44,840 --> 00:05:46,419
because they think we're going
to be a bunch of Hollywood...

95
00:05:46,720 --> 00:05:48,610
But they always come away with,
I'm sure, with a great respect.

96
00:05:48,960 --> 00:05:49,940
And they tell us that,

97
00:05:50,160 --> 00:05:52,760
that they come away with a great
respect for what we do,

98
00:05:53,200 --> 00:05:55,940
because they see it so
similar to the military.

99
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:08,840
So this was our first
transformation here.

100
00:06:09,280 --> 00:06:13,039
And the transformation was...
"How are we gonna do this, basically?"

101
00:06:13,640 --> 00:06:16,130
l had my animators do
tough versions of it.

102
00:06:16,560 --> 00:06:18,840
But when we had
this first version up...

103
00:06:19,240 --> 00:06:21,490
That was the very first version
l ever saw of that transformation.

104
00:06:21,960 --> 00:06:24,489
And it was done by
an artist named Keiji.

105
00:06:24,920 --> 00:06:27,620
He's Japanese.
He speaks like no English.

106
00:06:28,080 --> 00:06:31,770
He is the absolute Rubik's Cube
genius to figure those things out,

107
00:06:32,360 --> 00:06:35,690
of how those parts actually
move and come together.

108
00:06:37,680 --> 00:06:40,980
I met Keiji in a very odd meeting
at Industrial Light and Magic.

109
00:06:41,520 --> 00:06:46,859
I had about 30 ILM artists
sitting in a kind of hi-def room

110
00:06:47,720 --> 00:06:49,330
where we are looking
at the artwork

111
00:06:49,640 --> 00:06:52,870
that my illustrators had
worked for months,

112
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:55,260
I mean we're talking
eight months, on.

113
00:06:55,600 --> 00:06:58,860
And then I saw Optimus Prime's
face in his first 3-D kind of,

114
00:06:59,400 --> 00:07:02,070
I guess, iteration of him.

115
00:07:02,520 --> 00:07:05,930
He looked terrible.
He had this fat, ugly face.

116
00:07:06,480 --> 00:07:08,480
And I'm like, "You guys
got to be kidding me.

117
00:07:08,840 --> 00:07:10,729
"This is awful. What
happened to Optimus?"

118
00:07:11,080 --> 00:07:16,349
And all of a sudden, in this small room,
this guy pops up in the back,

119
00:07:17,160 --> 00:07:20,950
and he goes, "That Optimus Prime is
an insult to the Japanese people.

120
00:07:21,560 --> 00:07:23,950
"That is an insult to the Japanese,
l want to do Optimus Prime.”

121
00:07:24,360 --> 00:07:26,320
But you can tell someone else
was obviously modelling

122
00:07:26,680 --> 00:07:29,910
Optimus Prime's fat, ugly
face and Keiji knew this.

123
00:07:30,480 --> 00:07:33,530
And so I said, "Keiji, first of all, this
is the most bizarre meeting

124
00:07:34,040 --> 00:07:36,460
"Il have ever been to, the biggest,
funniest outbreak I have ever seen,

125
00:07:36,880 --> 00:07:37,860
"and you know what,
just because of that,

126
00:07:38,080 --> 00:07:39,969
"I'm gonna let you work
on Optimus Prime."

127
00:07:40,320 --> 00:07:43,730
So not only did Keiji do Optimus
Prime in terms of the 3-D modelling,

128
00:07:44,320 --> 00:07:46,670
but he did the amazing
Rubik's Cube

129
00:07:47,120 --> 00:07:51,190
of how we were going to
transform these robots.

130
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:59,700
What the military is very concerned
of when they do movies

131
00:08:00,200 --> 00:08:01,810
is that they just want things
to be accurate.

132
00:08:02,120 --> 00:08:04,190
They are very into, like,
those uniforms.

133
00:08:04,560 --> 00:08:07,190
If they are not Qatar-issue uniforms,
we just can't use them.

134
00:08:07,640 --> 00:08:09,500
Right here, I shot this
in the Tank Graveyard.

135
00:08:09,840 --> 00:08:12,510
These are old tanks, some are
just kind of shells of other tanks,

136
00:08:12,960 --> 00:08:15,210
where they actually put
them out in the field,

137
00:08:15,600 --> 00:08:17,810
in this white sand, and they
use them as target-practise.

138
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:25,930
We actually started the shoot,
the very first day was...

139
00:08:26,560 --> 00:08:30,600
I shot this little, I guess,
Mars rover. I shot that.

140
00:08:32,559 --> 00:08:33,750
I got it assembled because
I had this idea for a teaser

141
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:36,210
that was the very first teaser
that came out the summer

142
00:08:36,600 --> 00:08:39,620
where we just began to start...
We just started shooting.

143
00:08:40,120 --> 00:08:44,900
I just wanted to mark our date of
July 4th and to say we were real.

144
00:08:45,640 --> 00:08:48,410
The very first day of
pre-production photography,

145
00:08:48,880 --> 00:08:50,840
I shot in the Tank Graveyard.

146
00:08:51,200 --> 00:08:54,010
My first days really never
suck, but this one really sucked.

147
00:08:54,480 --> 00:08:56,410
I get to the set,
I'm all excited,

148
00:08:56,760 --> 00:08:58,790
and I'm walking around with
my viewfinder, ready to go.

149
00:08:59,200 --> 00:09:01,690
And I get on set
an hour before call

150
00:09:02,120 --> 00:09:05,240
and the hour passes and then
I'm waiting, "Okay, where's my crew?"

151
00:09:05,760 --> 00:09:07,270
I'm like, "This isn't good."

152
00:09:07,560 --> 00:09:09,699
My crew apparently was
just eating dinner.

153
00:09:10,080 --> 00:09:13,700
And normally when you
get to set, you show up,

154
00:09:14,280 --> 00:09:15,819
you either eat dinner before...

155
00:09:16,120 --> 00:09:20,160
So my cameraman, Mitchell Amundsen,
my operators, everyone's eating.

156
00:09:20,800 --> 00:09:24,209
And I'm like, "Okay." And that pissed me
off, the first night.

157
00:09:24,760 --> 00:09:26,900
So I'm like,
"Mitch, this is a big movie,

158
00:09:27,280 --> 00:09:29,100
"and you're not going to be
eating your burritos any more

159
00:09:29,440 --> 00:09:31,190
"when I show up to set and
I'm ready to work."

160
00:09:31,520 --> 00:09:36,510
So I think that kind of shook the
ground of everyone, the first night.

161
00:09:37,280 --> 00:09:39,100
Because I got to tell you,
when I come on the set

162
00:09:39,440 --> 00:09:41,830
I'm like, ! come in...
They joke on the set,

163
00:09:42,240 --> 00:09:43,400
"Bay's coming in hot."

164
00:09:43,640 --> 00:09:46,550
It means I like to work.
I don't like to fart around,

165
00:09:47,040 --> 00:09:51,010
and everyone knows that
I do a lot of set-ups every day.

166
00:09:51,640 --> 00:09:55,990
An average on a movie is 19 to 25.
I do 50, 60, sometimes 75.

167
00:09:56,680 --> 00:09:58,329
And these are real set-ups.

168
00:09:58,640 --> 00:10:03,800
And I shot a lot of this movie
very, kind of, suburbia.

169
00:10:04,600 --> 00:10:08,570
But I didn't kind of sex it up
in terms of making this slick.

170
00:10:09,200 --> 00:10:11,970
This is a classroom that we all
know about, we have all been to.

171
00:10:12,440 --> 00:10:17,250
And it's something that makes it
more accessible, I think, to everybody.

172
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:21,930
And like, I have never in my life
ever shot in a Burger King.

173
00:10:22,560 --> 00:10:25,300
But you know what? We all eat at
Burger King or McDonald's or whatever,

174
00:10:25,760 --> 00:10:27,790
and it just makes it
more everyday life.

175
00:10:28,160 --> 00:10:30,329
And I kind of like this,
kind of, sci-fi movie

176
00:10:30,720 --> 00:10:33,000
coupled with this suburbia life.

177
00:10:33,400 --> 00:10:35,860
I thought it was a good mix.

178
00:10:36,280 --> 00:10:38,069
And casting Shia...

179
00:10:38,400 --> 00:10:40,860
l actually started to
look for kids and I had...

180
00:10:41,280 --> 00:10:47,010
My casting ladies scoured the Earth for
the best 16, 17, 18, 19, 20-year-old kid

181
00:10:47,880 --> 00:10:50,090
that can play a 16-year-old
out there.

182
00:10:50,480 --> 00:10:52,800
And we looked from London to
Australia to Canada,

183
00:10:53,200 --> 00:10:57,200
and lan Bryce was the first to
mention to me Shia LaBeouf.

184
00:10:57,840 --> 00:11:00,370
Or "LaBoof." I call him
"Shia LeBuff.”

185
00:11:00,800 --> 00:11:02,870
I said, "Well, saw him
in Constantine,

186
00:11:03,240 --> 00:11:04,640
"and I have never seen
the movie Holes,

187
00:11:04,920 --> 00:11:07,620
"but in Constantine he was playing
a cab driver. He looked a little old."

188
00:11:08,080 --> 00:11:13,140
So the kid came in, and
he was kind of skinny

189
00:11:13,920 --> 00:11:17,469
and, like, a little goofy and
way over-excited.

190
00:11:18,040 --> 00:11:19,510
I'm like, "Dude, you
got to calm down here,

191
00:11:19,800 --> 00:11:22,849
"you're just auditioning with
me at my office.”

192
00:11:23,360 --> 00:11:26,590
And he goes, "Wow, I just...l want to be
an action guy and I want to be a...

193
00:11:27,120 --> 00:11:29,610
"It's just like, wow, I love your movies and
I can't believe I'm meeting you."

194
00:11:30,040 --> 00:11:34,040
I'm like, "All right, calm down,
let's just do the audition."

195
00:11:34,680 --> 00:11:40,719
And I just instantly liked his
energy in the audition.

196
00:11:41,640 --> 00:11:45,430
You know, we had some of our early,
early written pages,

197
00:11:46,040 --> 00:11:48,780
where the dialogue really needed
to be tweaked and made more real.

198
00:11:49,240 --> 00:11:51,840
And sometimes it's actually good to
read with some clunky dialogue,

199
00:11:52,280 --> 00:11:54,069
and you see how actors
could fare through,

200
00:11:54,400 --> 00:11:57,170
because a good actor can
make any line sound good.

201
00:11:57,640 --> 00:12:01,150
And Spielberg will even
tell you that.

202
00:12:01,720 --> 00:12:04,110
That's the art of acting,
.
In a way.

203
00:12:04,520 --> 00:12:06,170
But I started throwing some
stuff to Shia,

204
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:09,110
like improv-ing with him a bit
in the audition.

205
00:12:09,560 --> 00:12:12,089
My thing is I love finding actors
that can improv

206
00:12:12,520 --> 00:12:16,170
because a lot of my film-making,
.
we Improv as we go.

207
00:12:16,760 --> 00:12:18,580
I mean, we have the basis
of the scene.

208
00:12:18,920 --> 00:12:22,819
I mean, I kind of learned this on working
with Martin and Will on Bad Boys.

209
00:12:23,440 --> 00:12:25,260
Shia just had this great thing.

210
00:12:25,600 --> 00:12:29,710
And, you know, I called Steven,
and I said, "I met with Shia.”

211
00:12:30,360 --> 00:12:34,430
And Steven goes, "I love Shia."
So he was all excited about that.

212
00:12:35,080 --> 00:12:38,660
And I said, "Well, I really want
to show you this tape."

213
00:12:39,240 --> 00:12:42,720
l went downstairs and because I had
auditioned a couple of other kids

214
00:12:43,280 --> 00:12:48,900
and he just was heads and tails
above every other kid that came in.

215
00:12:49,760 --> 00:12:51,480
And I asked the girls
in the office,

216
00:12:51,800 --> 00:12:53,550
my assistants who are
very blunt, I said,

217
00:12:53,880 --> 00:12:54,820
"So what do you think
of him?"

218
00:12:55,040 --> 00:12:57,849
I said, "Just watch the DVD,
watch his video."

219
00:12:58,320 --> 00:13:00,420
They saw and they go like,
"Oh, my God, he's great, he's great.

220
00:13:00,800 --> 00:13:03,290
"He's so funny, he's so charming,
he's so funny."

221
00:13:03,720 --> 00:13:05,680
So I sent the audition to
Steven,

222
00:13:06,040 --> 00:13:07,650
and then I called Shia back.

223
